2026-04-21 01:36:01 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Battery internal resistor / series element in power supply module'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show the battery itself is good (12 V both open‑circuit and under load) and there is low ohmic continuity from the battery clips to the PSU output and LED branch at low test current. However, when powered, all points on the supposed + rail—including PSU output +, LED resistor, and LED anode—sit at ~0.012 V, while battery − is at 0 V. A critical clue is the test on the internal series resistor (or protection element) between the battery and the rail: its terminal marked (+) is at ~0.012 V while its (−) terminal is at 12 V, i.e., the voltage appears inverted across that part, which is consistent with that resistor (or a protection component in that position) being open / burnt / very high resistance or miswired, so the downstream circuit only sees leakage, not the 12 V source. Because continuity at low current still appears normal, this points to a component that has failed under load (e.g., cracked solder joint or internally damaged resistor/PTC/fuse) but measures low resistance when probed with the meter. Replacing this internal series element that connects battery + to the PSU positive rail should restore 12 V to the green LED branch, the control modules, and the load, resolving the remaining fault.'
